title: Economic Expansion
subtitle: The economy is growing steadily.
new-page: true
view-if: economic_expansion >= 85 and unemployed <= 6 and inflation <= 6 and spd_in_government
on-arrival: economic_expansion = 0; expansion_seen += 1; capital_strike_progress -= 2 if capital_strike_progress >= 2 and not class_war; capital_strike_progress -= 1 if peoples_party and left_split and not capital_rejected; budget += 1; workers_spd += 4*(1-dissent) if spd_in_government; new_middle_spd += 2*(1-dissent) if spd_in_government; old_middle_spd += 2*(1-dissent) if spd_in_government; rural_spd += 2*(1-dissent) if spd_in_government; new_middle_ddp += 5 if in_weimar_coalition or in_grand_coalition or in_popular_front; workers_kpd += 3 if in_popular_front or in_left_front; old_middle_dvp += 4 if in_grand_coalition; new_middle_dvp += 3 if in_grand_coalition; inflation += 0.4; socialism += class_war if class_war; socialism -= ((reformist_strength/10)*bourgeois_power) if not in_popular_front or in_left_front
tags: event

= Economic Expansion

The German economy has been growing steadily for an extended period of time, and has low inflation and unemployment. The government is rewarded by additional tax revenue from the same tax rates. [? if not class_war : Even the capitalists find that they have little to complain about when it comes to government policies. ?][? if class_war : The success of our economy is attributed to socialism, which is finding widespread support. ?] One downside of this economic growth, however, is the rising risk of inflation.

[? if capital_strike_progress < 0 and expansion_seen >= 2 and not in_grand_coalition and peoples_party : The economic growth under our governance has reached such a point that some industrialists are coming around to social democracy, at least under the form we have taken. ?]

- @welcome_industry: [? if not capital_spd : Well, a people's party is a people's party... ?][? if capital_spd : <span style="color:rgb(170,150,60);font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.5px;">Pleasure doing business as usual.</span> ?]
- @ew: It's nice that they don't want open conflict, but we still oppose their interests.

@welcome_industry
view-if: capital_strike_progress < 0 and expansion_seen >= 2 and not in_grand_coalition and peoples_party
subtitle: +3 resources
on-arrival: resources += 3; bourgeois_power += 0.02; left_dissent += 10; center_dissent += 10; labor_dissent += 5; bourgeoisie_spd += (2*economic_growth)*(1-dissent); bourgeoisie_dvp -= economic_growth; socialism -= (spd_votes*bourgeois_power)/10; capital_spd += 2; old_middle_spd += 5*bourgeois_power; new_middle_spd += 5*bourgeois_power; rural_spd += (5-land_reform)*bourgeois_power; kpd_relation -= 20

We are not a party to turn away supports just because of their economic class; we abandoned that practice when we become a people's party. Corporations are people, too. It's only a natural progression of our policy.

@ew
view-if: capital_strike_progress < 0 and expansion_seen >= 2 and not in_grand_coalition and peoples_party
unavailable-subtitle: <span style="color:rgb(170,150,60);font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.5px;">Who's we? I'm not!</span>
choose-if: not capital_spd
on-arrival: capital_rejected = 1; capital_strike_progress = 2

We're a party for the people against the elites; and, while it's great that we are able to constructively govern without obstruction by capital, we are still fundamentally against them. This will never change.

## if the DVP is in government, the economic growth is just credited to DVP policy